{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RJHuJDE1NKJbbTiPB9xC9p","type":"tool_result","content":"apiVersion: v1\ndata:\n  findings.txt: |-\n    === SPARK-PI NAMESPACE COMPLIANCE AUDIT ===\n    Date: 2026-06-16\n    Auditor: Automated read-only inspection\n    Scope: RBAC, resource limits, image provenance, job security context, network policies\n\n    --- SECTION 1: RBAC ---\n\n    [PASS] Dedicated ServiceAccount 'spark-pi' exists; workloads do not run as the 'default' SA.\n    [PASS] Role 'spark-pi-role' is namespace-scoped (Role, not ClusterRole) — no cluster-wide privilege escalation.\n    [PASS] RoleBinding 'spark-pi-role-binding' correctly binds 'spark-pi-role' to SA 'spark-pi' within the namespace.\n    [PASS] No ClusterRole or ClusterRoleBinding found for this workload — blast radius is limited to the spark-pi namespace.\n\n    [GAP]  Role 'spark-pi-role' grants 'delete', 'update', and 'patch' on 'pods', 'configmaps', 'services', and\n           'persistentvolumeclaims'. The delete verb on pods in particular is overly broad; a compromised driver\n           could terminate arbitrary pods in the namespace. Recommend scoping verbs to the minimum needed (e.g.,\n           remove 'delete' on pods if the job does not require it).\n\n    --- SECTION 2: RESOURCE LIMITS ---\n\n    [PASS] spark-master deployment: requests cpu=200m/memory=512Mi, limits cpu=500m/memory=1Gi — limits set.\n    [PASS] spark-worker deployment: requests cpu=200m/memory=512Mi, limits cpu=500m/memory=1Gi — limits set.\n    [PASS] spark-pi job (spark-submit container): requests cpu=200m/memory=512Mi, limits cpu=500m/memory=1Gi — limits set.\n    [PASS] All three workloads have both requests and limits defined; no unbounded resource consumption possible.\n\n    --- SECTION 3: IMAGE PROVENANCE ---\n\n    [PASS] All containers (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-submit) use a pinned version tag: apache/spark:3.5.3.\n           The 'latest' tag is not used anywhere.\n\n    [GAP]  Image tags are mutable; 'apache/spark:3.5.3' could be overwritten in the registry without changing the\n           manifest. No image digest (sha256) pinning is present. Recommend pinning to\n           apache/spark@sha256:<digest> to guarantee immutable provenance.\n\n    [INFO] imagePullPolicy is 'IfNotPresent' on all containers. This prevents unnecessary re-pulls but means a\n           cached image with a reassigned tag will not be detected. Combined with digest pinning this would be\n           acceptable; without it, the policy reduces the chance of pulling a tampered image but is not a\n           substitue for digest pinning.\n\n    --- SECTION 4: JOB / POD SECURITY CONTEXT ---\n\n    [GAP]  spark-master deployment: pod-level securityContext is empty ({}). No runAsNonRoot, runAsUser,\n           fsGroup, or seccompProfile configured. Container may run as root (UID 0).\n\n    [GAP]  spark-worker deployment: pod-level securityContext is empty ({}). Same issues as spark-master.\n\n    [GAP]  spark-pi job: pod-level securityContext is empty ({}). The spark-submit container runs with no\n           security restrictions.\n\n    [GAP]  No container-level securityContext is set on any container. Specifically missing:\n             - allowPrivilegeEscalation: false\n             - readOnlyRootFilesystem: true (or explicit false with justification)\n             - capabilities.drop: [\"ALL\"]\n             - runAsNonRoot: true\n           These omissions mean containers have the default (permissive) Linux capability set and may\n           run as root, violating least-privilege and CIS Kubernetes Benchmark controls 5.2.x.\n\n    --- SECTION 5: NETWORK POLICIES ---\n\n    [GAP]  No NetworkPolicy resources exist in the spark-pi namespace. All pods can freely communicate\n           with any other pod in any namespace and can initiate outbound connections without restriction.\n           Recommend adding a default-deny ingress/egress policy and explicit allow rules for only the\n           required Spark traffic (driver ↔ master port 7077, master ↔ worker port 8081, web UI port 8080).\n\n    --- SUMMARY ---\n\n    Correctly configured (PASS): 7 controls\n      - Dedicated service account (not default)\n      - Namespace-scoped Role only (no ClusterRole)\n      - RoleBinding correctly wired\n      - No cluster-wide RBAC grants\n      - Resource requests and limits set on all three workloads\n      - Specific image version tag used (not 'latest')\n\n    Gaps requiring remediation: 6 controls\n      1. [RBAC]     Role grants overly broad verbs (delete/update/patch on pods/configmaps/pvcs).\n      2. [IMAGE]    No image digest (sha256) pinning — mutable tags in use.\n      3. [SECCTX]   spark-master pod security context absent — potential root execution.\n      4. [SECCTX]   spark-worker pod security context absent — potential root execution.\n      5. [SECCTX]   spark-pi job pod security context absent — potential root execution; no privilege\n                    drop, no allowPrivilegeEscalation:false, no capability restrictions on any container.\n      6. [NETPOL]   No NetworkPolicy — unrestricted inter-namespace and egress traffic.\nkind: ConfigMap\nmetadata:\n  creationTimestamp: \"2026-06-16T10:05:38Z\"\n  name: config-audit\n  namespace: spark-pi\n  resourceVersion: \"62742\"\n  uid: a60bb9c6-b1c7-4fff-9537-cb921f8144b9","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7ed9bf79-e2dd-4c8c-a459-ba0f89715c35","uuid":"4fef9bee-449f-4d91-9e69-87738140cd35","timestamp":"2026-06-16T10:06:31.808Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"apiVersion: v1\ndata:\n  findings.txt: |-\n    === SPARK-PI NAMESPACE COMPLIANCE AUDIT ===\n    Date: 2026-06-16\n    Auditor: Automated read-only inspection\n    Scope: RBAC, resource limits, image provenance, job security context, network policies\n\n    --- SECTION 1: RBAC ---\n\n    [PASS] Dedicated ServiceAccount 'spark-pi' exists; workloads do not run as the 'default' SA.\n    [PASS